WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.790 --> 00:00:05.000
&gt;&gt; From the Library of
Congress in Washington DC.

00:00:19.300 --> 00:00:20.600 position:56%
&gt;&gt; David Mao: Good morning everyone.

00:00:20.600 --> 00:00:22.220
Well-- I feel like I
should be standing here

00:00:22.220 --> 00:00:23.520
and singing the national anthem.

00:00:23.520 --> 00:00:24.820
But I don't want to
scare anybody away

00:00:24.820 --> 00:00:27.000
since we have a nice crowd here.

00:00:27.000 --> 00:00:29.060
My name is David Mao and I
have the honor of serving

00:00:29.060 --> 00:00:30.830 position:56%
as the acting Librarian of Congress.

00:00:30.830 --> 00:00:33.260
Welcome to the Library of Congress.

00:00:33.260 --> 00:00:36.390
It is our nation's oldest,
Federal, cultural institution.

00:00:36.390 --> 00:00:38.790
Excuse me, I should say our first,
Federal, cultural institution.

00:00:38.790 --> 00:00:41.180
And we are just so
delighted that all

00:00:41.180 --> 00:00:43.460
of you could be with us here today.

00:00:43.460 --> 00:00:46.390
We are the Library of
Congress and we were created

00:00:46.390 --> 00:00:49.940
by Congress 216-- almost
216 years ago.

00:00:49.940 --> 00:00:52.520
And have been generously supported
by Congress over the years

00:00:52.520 --> 00:00:55.160
to become the world's
largest library.

00:00:55.160 --> 00:00:58.200
And we're very proud of that fact.

00:00:58.200 --> 00:01:01.460
But we are the nation's library
but as our name suggests.

00:01:01.460 --> 00:01:03.200
We are the Library for Congress.

00:01:03.200 --> 00:01:05.440 position:56%
And so that's why I think it's
particularly appropriate that we are

00:01:05.440 --> 00:01:09.140
in this room today for
this very special program.

00:01:09.140 --> 00:01:14.200
This room in this building when
it was opened in 189-- 1897.

00:01:14.200 --> 00:01:17.270
Served as the reading room for
the House of Representatives.

00:01:17.270 --> 00:01:19.930
And today it's known as the
member's room and reserved

00:01:19.930 --> 00:01:22.510
for the use of members of Congress.

00:01:22.510 --> 00:01:25.320
And so with that, we're
very delighted to have

00:01:25.320 --> 00:01:27.900 position:56%
with us 2 members of Congress today.

00:01:27.900 --> 00:01:32.070
In this room, to tell us a
little bit about their careers.

00:01:32.070 --> 00:01:33.670
Chairman Candice Miller
from Michigan

00:01:33.670 --> 00:01:36.390
and Representative Janice
Hahn from California.

00:01:36.390 --> 00:01:38.330
They're here to kick
off our celebration

00:01:38.330 --> 00:01:40.640
of women's history month.

00:01:40.640 --> 00:01:41.940
Both Chairman Miller

00:01:41.940 --> 00:01:44.770
and Representative Hahn have
had distinguished careers

00:01:44.770 --> 00:01:46.070
in public service.

00:01:46.070 --> 00:01:48.610
And so we're very much looking
forward to hearing from them.

00:01:48.610 --> 00:01:50.260
Their thoughts about
their time in Congress.

00:01:50.260 --> 00:01:52.680
And in particular the
role that gender plays

00:01:52.680 --> 00:01:55.960
in today's political
leadership and landscape.

00:01:55.960 --> 00:01:58.540
Our discussion will
be lead and moderated

00:01:58.540 --> 00:02:01.180
by my colleague, Doctor
Colleen Shogan.

00:02:01.180 --> 00:02:02.840
Who is the director
of our national--

00:02:02.840 --> 00:02:05.440
excuse me, Deputy Director
of National

00:02:05.440 --> 00:02:08.790
and International Outreach
here at the library.

00:02:08.790 --> 00:02:13.200
Today's topic though, of course, is
of particular interest to Colleen.

00:02:13.200 --> 00:02:15.150
Because as the former
Deputy Director

00:02:15.150 --> 00:02:16.780
of the Congressional
Research Service.

00:02:16.780 --> 00:02:20.490 position:56%
She had authored at her time in CRS,

00:02:20.490 --> 00:02:24.410
an often cited CRS report
on Women in Congress.

00:02:24.410 --> 00:02:28.290
So-- please join me in welcoming
all of our distinguished members

00:02:28.290 --> 00:02:30.940
of Congress and Doctor
Colleen Shogan.

00:02:30.940 --> 00:02:36.210
Thank you [applause].

00:02:36.210 --> 00:02:38.040
&gt;&gt; Colleen Shogan: Welcome
to the Library of Congress

00:02:38.040 --> 00:02:40.600
and this beautiful
room this morning.

00:02:40.600 --> 00:02:43.660
As at the end of our
program we hope to have time

00:02:43.660 --> 00:02:45.960
for questions from the audience.

00:02:45.960 --> 00:02:49.490
But I'm going to kick
it off this morning.

00:02:49.490 --> 00:02:54.070
You both have had very long and
distinguished careers in politics.

00:02:54.070 --> 00:02:57.530
But you both had different
entries into public service.

00:02:57.530 --> 00:03:01.960
So can you tell us about how
and why you became interested

00:03:01.960 --> 00:03:04.520
in government service
in the first place?

00:03:04.520 --> 00:03:06.400
Chairman Miller.

00:03:06.400 --> 00:03:09.840
&gt;&gt; Rep. Candice Miller: Well
for me, I live in-- Chairman--

00:03:09.840 --> 00:03:12.100
or David Mao was just talking
about the tenth district.

00:03:12.100 --> 00:03:16.030
You know, in Michigan we have a map
of the state on the end of our arm.

00:03:16.030 --> 00:03:18.670
So I-- live in this area here.

00:03:18.670 --> 00:03:20.480
This is my-- district.

00:03:20.480 --> 00:03:26.520
And-- on the Great Lakes and my
family was in the marina business.

00:03:26.520 --> 00:03:28.920
So I actually sold
boats for a living.

00:03:28.920 --> 00:03:32.690
And-- I raised sailboats and
that was sort of our-- hobby.

00:03:32.690 --> 00:03:36.320
And our way we made our
living, our social-- everything.

00:03:36.320 --> 00:03:38.620
Everything was boating oriented.

00:03:38.620 --> 00:03:42.980
And when I was in my mid-20's,

00:03:42.980 --> 00:03:45.450
the local township
decided they were going

00:03:45.450 --> 00:03:47.540
to pass an ordinance
to tax all the marinas.

00:03:47.540 --> 00:03:50.360
Because about 40% of
the commercial tax base

00:03:50.360 --> 00:03:53.740
in our area is all marina oriented.

00:03:53.740 --> 00:03:55.990
And in a family business
you do everything.

00:03:55.990 --> 00:03:57.410
I mean everything, right?

00:03:57.410 --> 00:03:59.740
From doing the books to
selling boats to whatever.

00:03:59.740 --> 00:04:01.390
And I remember telling--
I was doing the books.

00:04:01.390 --> 00:04:03.020
And I remember telling my dad.

00:04:03.020 --> 00:04:04.560 position:56%
I said, "We just can't afford this!"

00:04:04.560 --> 00:04:06.780
They were going to tax so
much for wet storage in the--

00:04:06.780 --> 00:04:08.570
in the water storage,
so much for dry storage.

00:04:08.570 --> 00:04:09.870
And I said-- you-- I don't know.

00:04:09.870 --> 00:04:11.620
I probably said, "Taxation
without representation"

00:04:11.620 --> 00:04:13.260
or I don't know what
I was saying you know.

00:04:13.260 --> 00:04:14.980
And my dad sort of
padded me on the head.

00:04:14.980 --> 00:04:16.780
He says, "Oh no-- " Because
he used to call me Candy--

00:04:16.780 --> 00:04:18.690
don't tell anyone that
but-- [laughter].

00:04:18.690 --> 00:04:20.480
Yes, yes but then when
I ran for office I said,

00:04:20.480 --> 00:04:22.020
"I have to be Candice now."

00:04:22.020 --> 00:04:24.160
But anyway, he said,
"Well Candy, you know,

00:04:24.160 --> 00:04:26.050
you can't-- fight city hall so-- "

00:04:26.050 --> 00:04:27.350
&gt;&gt; Colleen Shogan: Right.

00:04:27.350 --> 00:04:28.650
Right.

00:04:28.650 --> 00:04:29.950
&gt;&gt; Rep. Candice Miller: "You
know, this is what we got to do."

00:04:29.950 --> 00:04:31.250
I said, "Well then-- " I
just couldn't believe it.

00:04:31.250 --> 00:04:32.550
So I went around to
all these marinas

00:04:32.550 --> 00:04:33.850
and got these petitions signed.

00:04:33.850 --> 00:04:35.570
And long story, short went
into the township off--

00:04:35.570 --> 00:04:37.370
the township board meeting.

00:04:37.370 --> 00:04:39.860 position:56%
And you know, gosh I was so riled up

00:04:39.860 --> 00:04:41.420
but I was sitting way
in the back of the room.

00:04:41.420 --> 00:04:44.850
And I'll never forget when
they got to our-- agenda item.

00:04:44.850 --> 00:04:47.350
All these guys that own the
marina said, "Okay, you know,

00:04:47.350 --> 00:04:48.650
get up there and tell them."

00:04:48.650 --> 00:04:49.950
And I went [Gasp].

00:04:49.950 --> 00:04:51.250
I still can remember
my heart pounding.

00:04:51.250 --> 00:04:52.970
Because I had never spoken
publicly or anything.

00:04:52.970 --> 00:04:54.780
Never thought about politics.

00:04:54.780 --> 00:04:56.080
And sometimes for me,

00:04:56.080 --> 00:05:00.310
I think anxiety almost
manifests itself in anger.

00:05:00.310 --> 00:05:01.970
So I was like, "Listen!

00:05:01.970 --> 00:05:04.530
[laughs] can't do this".

00:05:04.530 --> 00:05:05.830
And we were successful.

00:05:05.830 --> 00:05:07.130
I thought, "Oh my gosh!

00:05:07.130 --> 00:05:09.970
If you're really obnoxious you
could become a politician!"

00:05:09.970 --> 00:05:13.150
You know [laughs] so
then I'm looking

00:05:13.150 --> 00:05:14.840
at all these other
people on the board.

00:05:14.840 --> 00:05:16.540
And it thought, "Hey
I could do that."

00:05:16.540 --> 00:05:20.500
So then I ran, I was too young
to know I wouldn't win but I won.

00:05:20.500 --> 00:05:24.030
And that's-- here I am.

00:05:24.030 --> 00:05:25.790
&gt;&gt; Colleen Shogan:
Representative Hahn.

00:05:25.790 --> 00:05:30.470
&gt;&gt; Rep. Janice Hahn: Well I had
a-- sort of a different entry.

00:05:30.470 --> 00:05:32.780
You know your family was
in boating and marinas.

00:05:32.780 --> 00:05:35.830
My family actually was in politics.

00:05:35.830 --> 00:05:38.350
So it's really everything
we talked about.

00:05:38.350 --> 00:05:40.250
We talked about politics
at the dinner table.

00:05:40.250 --> 00:05:48.470
My dad was a 46 year elected
official in Los Angeles County.

00:05:48.470 --> 00:05:52.240
My brother was the City
Controller, the City attorney

00:05:52.240 --> 00:05:54.400
and then the Mayor of Los Angeles.

00:05:54.400 --> 00:05:57.930
So our family-- it was
really our family business.

00:05:57.930 --> 00:06:01.300
I didn't quite embrace it.

00:06:01.300 --> 00:06:07.440
In the beginning, I actually
have my teaching credential--

00:06:07.440 --> 00:06:08.760
my secondary teaching credential.

00:06:08.760 --> 00:06:11.370
I actually taught junior
high and high school.

00:06:11.370 --> 00:06:15.350
I went into small business.

00:06:15.350 --> 00:06:18.090
I worked for an investor-owned
utility.

00:06:18.090 --> 00:06:20.250
I worked for a trash company.

00:06:20.250 --> 00:06:25.280 position:56%
I sort of did all these other things
and then I think it just hit me.

00:06:25.280 --> 00:06:28.280
The DNA kicked in.

00:06:28.280 --> 00:06:31.220
It's one of those moments
where you're sort of,

00:06:31.220 --> 00:06:32.610
you know, lying in bed at night.

00:06:32.610 --> 00:06:34.020
And you're like, "You know what?

00:06:34.020 --> 00:06:35.650
What am I supposed
to be doing here?"

00:06:35.650 --> 00:06:42.410
And it was very clear to me that
the best way I could affect change

00:06:42.410 --> 00:06:46.460
in my community and my neighborhood
was to run for-- public office.

00:06:46.460 --> 00:06:48.770
I lost my first race.

00:06:48.770 --> 00:06:51.710
I was like the first
member of my family

00:06:51.710 --> 00:06:53.880
to ever lose in a race [laughter].

00:06:53.880 --> 00:06:58.450
It was very humiliating
and embarrassing.

00:06:58.450 --> 00:06:59.750
But you know what?

00:06:59.750 --> 00:07:01.480
I knew that that's
what I wanted to do.

00:07:01.480 --> 00:07:04.480
And then 8 years later I
ran again and was elected

00:07:04.480 --> 00:07:06.010
to the Los Angeles City Council.

00:07:06.010 --> 00:07:09.290
You know I waited so
long to actually--

00:07:09.290 --> 00:07:11.110
it wasn't until I was 49 or 50

00:07:11.110 --> 00:07:14.130
when I actually had my
first elected office.

00:07:14.130 --> 00:07:19.570
And so, sort of funny that
finally when I got elected in 2001.

00:07:19.570 --> 00:07:23.250
It was the same night that
my brother was elected Mayor.

00:07:23.250 --> 00:07:26.220
So [laughter] I joke
that even my mother went

00:07:26.220 --> 00:07:27.970
to his victory party, you know?

00:07:27.970 --> 00:07:30.060
[laughter].

00:07:30.060 --> 00:07:34.360
That's how I got into politics.

00:07:34.360 --> 00:07:37.750
&gt;&gt; Colleen Shogan: At a certain
point one day you both decided

00:07:37.750 --> 00:07:39.290
