00:09:55.860 --> 00:09:58.350
And of course both
of us are deciding

00:09:58.350 --> 00:10:00.190
to do something else
with our-- lives, right?

00:10:00.190 --> 00:10:02.810
We both have another dance
in us, whatever that is.

00:10:02.810 --> 00:10:06.180
So-- I'm just finishing
my seventh term.

00:10:06.180 --> 00:10:10.630
Which has been the most incredible
experience I have ever had.

00:10:10.630 --> 00:10:11.930 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Colleen Shogan: Yeah, absolutely.

00:10:11.930 --> 00:10:13.490
Representative Hahn.

00:10:13.490 --> 00:10:20.720 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Rep. Janice Hahn: So that after I
lost the city council race in 1993.

00:10:20.720 --> 00:10:25.530
Until I won the city
council in 2001.

00:10:25.530 --> 00:10:29.430
Those you know 8 years,
I was really focused on--

00:10:29.430 --> 00:10:31.110
I was a single mother at the time.

00:10:31.110 --> 00:10:33.410
I was raising my 3 kids.

00:10:33.410 --> 00:10:35.120
I was an investment banker.

00:10:35.120 --> 00:10:38.230
This was when I was
really just focusing

00:10:38.230 --> 00:10:40.450
on you know jobs and making money.

00:10:40.450 --> 00:10:47.490 position:56%
And in 1998, my member of
Congress, Jane Harman decided to run

00:10:47.490 --> 00:10:50.080
for Governor of California.

00:10:50.080 --> 00:10:54.910
So she stepped down and now that
I'm back here I understand how the

00:10:54.910 --> 00:10:56.820
individual caucuses work.

00:10:56.820 --> 00:10:59.500
And if some member wants
to give up their seat.

00:10:59.500 --> 00:11:04.870
Man, it is a full court press
to find a good candidate to run

00:11:04.870 --> 00:11:06.870
in their race and replace them.

00:11:06.870 --> 00:11:09.840
So they came after me [noise].

00:11:09.840 --> 00:11:14.430
It's the ghost of former
members [laughter] which is

00:11:14.430 --> 00:11:16.720
where we're going to be very soon.

00:11:16.720 --> 00:11:18.740
&gt;&gt; Rep. Candice Miller:
We'll be back here haunting.

00:11:18.740 --> 00:11:20.040
&gt;&gt; Rep. Janice Hahn: Yes, right.

00:11:20.040 --> 00:11:22.410
So I got phone calls
from Steny Hoyer.

00:11:22.410 --> 00:11:24.440
I never heard of Steny Hoyer.

00:11:24.440 --> 00:11:26.930
I got-- actually got a call
from President Clinton.

00:11:26.930 --> 00:11:32.350
Vice President Gore, they were
all trying to recruit someone

00:11:32.350 --> 00:11:35.770
who had a similar profile
to Jane Harman, right?

00:11:35.770 --> 00:11:37.750 position:56%
A woman, same initials-- [laughter].

00:11:37.750 --> 00:11:44.130
I-- in my heart of
hearts wasn't feeling it.

00:11:44.130 --> 00:11:47.620
But I-- it got to the sort of
answering the call to my country.

00:11:47.620 --> 00:11:52.400
You know, they're really asking me
to do this so I did it and lost.

00:11:52.400 --> 00:11:57.710 position:56%
It was apparently one of the closest
congressional races in the country.

00:11:57.710 --> 00:12:00.070
Lost by just 2 percentage points

00:12:00.070 --> 00:12:02.260
which is not very much
in a congressional race.

00:12:02.260 --> 00:12:03.560
But you know what?

00:12:03.560 --> 00:12:05.800
It's like the best thing
that ever happened to me.

00:12:05.800 --> 00:12:07.950
I do believe that things
happen for a reason.

00:12:07.950 --> 00:12:11.020
You don't always know it
when you're going through it.

00:12:11.020 --> 00:12:12.900
And it's never fun to lose.

00:12:12.900 --> 00:12:17.120
But as a result of me not
going to Congress in 1998.

00:12:17.120 --> 00:12:20.760
That's when then I was elected
to the local city council.

00:12:20.760 --> 00:12:24.880
And I got to cut my own political
teeth at the local level.

00:12:24.880 --> 00:12:28.050
And that was important
for me as a woman.

00:12:28.050 --> 00:12:33.840
I sort of grew up being the
daughter of-- and the sister of--

00:12:33.840 --> 00:12:37.940
these 2 very successful make
politicians in Los Angeles County.

00:12:37.940 --> 00:12:40.880
So it was really important for
me to cut my own political teeth

00:12:40.880 --> 00:12:42.730
in the Los Angeles City Council.

00:12:42.730 --> 00:12:44.880
So for 10 years I served there.

00:12:44.880 --> 00:12:48.120
We also have term limits
in City Council.

00:12:48.120 --> 00:12:51.190
So I was bumping up to my 12 years.

00:12:51.190 --> 00:12:54.120
And once again, Jane Harman.

00:12:54.120 --> 00:12:56.950
She went back and after I lost.

00:12:56.950 --> 00:12:58.960
She was like, "Well clearly
Janice couldn't do that.

00:12:58.960 --> 00:13:01.790
I have to come back
and win that seat."

00:13:01.790 --> 00:13:04.750
And then she called me again
one early February morning.

00:13:04.750 --> 00:13:09.090
And said, "I'm resigning
from Congress this week.

00:13:09.090 --> 00:13:11.440
And I think you ought
to run for my seat."

00:13:11.440 --> 00:13:13.640
So thought about it.

00:13:13.640 --> 00:13:16.720
You know, kind of called
my political consultants

00:13:16.720 --> 00:13:19.260
and we had our website
up by noon [laughter].

00:13:19.260 --> 00:13:21.730
And this time it felt right.

00:13:21.730 --> 00:13:23.030
It felt good.

00:13:23.030 --> 00:13:28.780
And so I was elected in 2011
in the special election.

00:13:28.780 --> 00:13:30.360
&gt;&gt; Colleen Shogan:
Throughout your careers,

00:13:30.360 --> 00:13:35.870
you both witnessed a transformation
of women's political participation

00:13:35.870 --> 00:13:38.530
in particularly electoral politics.

00:13:38.530 --> 00:13:41.330
Can you tell us how has
that transformation?

00:13:41.330 --> 00:13:44.540
How has that evolution
affected you personally?

00:13:44.540 --> 00:13:47.840
From the time in which you
began your public service.

00:13:47.840 --> 00:13:49.310
When you began your career.

00:13:49.310 --> 00:13:54.180
How it was then to what you
see now as more women start

00:13:54.180 --> 00:13:58.100
to participate in electoral
politics?

00:13:58.100 --> 00:13:59.400
&gt;&gt; Rep. Candice Miller: Me first?

00:13:59.400 --> 00:14:00.700
&gt;&gt; Colleen Shogan: Sure go ahead.

00:14:00.700 --> 00:14:02.000
&gt;&gt; Rep. Candice Miller: You
know I would just say this.

00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:04.600
I think-- when I was-- when I
was first running for office.

00:14:04.600 --> 00:14:06.880
I was also a single
mother at that time.

00:14:06.880 --> 00:14:08.430
And I couldn't afford a babysitter.

00:14:08.430 --> 00:14:11.270
And I dragged my little
daughter around.

00:14:11.270 --> 00:14:13.980 position:56%
Whose now in her 40's and the mother

00:14:13.980 --> 00:14:15.730
of the world's 2 most
beautiful grandchildren.

00:14:15.730 --> 00:14:17.030
But I--

00:14:17.030 --> 00:14:18.330
&gt;&gt; Rep. Janice Hahn:
Wait until you see mine.

00:14:18.330 --> 00:14:19.630
&gt;&gt; Rep. Candice Miller: Know
you would argue with that one.

00:14:19.630 --> 00:14:20.930
&gt;&gt; Rep. Janice Hahn: I know.

00:14:20.930 --> 00:14:22.230
&gt;&gt; Rep. Candice Miller:
But I dragged her

00:14:22.230 --> 00:14:23.530
around the neighborhoods
going door to door in a wagon.

00:14:23.530 --> 00:14:24.830
I tried to make a game
out of it, you know?

00:14:24.830 --> 00:14:26.130
Because I just couldn't
afford a sitter.

00:14:26.130 --> 00:14:28.890
And there we-- and people
were looking at me going.

00:14:28.890 --> 00:14:30.190
First I was young, right?

00:14:30.190 --> 00:14:32.810
I mean in my 20's but
then more than that.

00:14:32.810 --> 00:14:35.320
They'd say, "I mean
you're like a woman."

00:14:35.320 --> 00:14:36.620
&gt;&gt; Colleen Shogan: Right.

00:14:36.620 --> 00:14:37.920
&gt;&gt; Rep. Candice Miller:
Seriously, you know?

00:14:37.920 --> 00:14:39.220
"What are you doing?

00:14:39.220 --> 00:14:40.520
And now you want to be
you know the supervisor?

00:14:40.520 --> 00:14:41.820
Oh yeah right."

00:14:41.820 --> 00:14:45.250
And so I was the first female
supervisor in my community.

00:14:45.250 --> 00:14:47.480
And then I was the
first County Treasurer

00:14:47.480 --> 00:14:48.980
in my County-- first woman.

00:14:48.980 --> 00:14:52.110
Then I was the first woman
secretary of state in Michigan.

00:14:52.110 --> 00:14:53.470
&gt;&gt; Colleen Shogan:
There's a theme here.

00:14:53.470 --> 00:14:54.770
&gt;&gt; Rep. Candice Miller: You know?

00:14:54.770 --> 00:14:57.580
Well-- but you know all of these
things and sometimes you know I'm--

00:14:57.580 --> 00:14:59.230
as you might know I'm
the only woman chairman.

00:14:59.230 --> 00:15:00.530
&gt;&gt; Colleen Shogan: Right.

00:15:00.530 --> 00:15:01.830
&gt;&gt; Rep. Candice Miller: In
the House of Representatives.

00:15:01.830 --> 00:15:03.130
&gt;&gt; Colleen Shogan: Yes.

00:15:03.130 --> 00:15:04.430
&gt;&gt; Rep. Candice Miller: But you
know what the truth is really.

00:15:04.430 --> 00:15:05.730
I mean I got the whole woman thing.

00:15:05.730 --> 00:15:07.230
But I've never really, you know.

00:15:07.230 --> 00:15:08.620
"Oh you're the woman
member of Congress."

00:15:08.620 --> 00:15:09.920
I'm like, "Well I don't know.

00:15:09.920 --> 00:15:11.800
I'm like the-- I'm the
member of Congress.

00:15:11.800 --> 00:15:15.080
And in issues that they
talk about for women."

00:15:15.080 --> 00:15:17.840
I think all issues are
women's issues, you know.

00:15:17.840 --> 00:15:19.220
Sometimes they'll say,
"Oh well okay.

00:15:19.220 --> 00:15:20.520
Here's the health issues.

00:15:20.520 --> 00:15:24.040
Now, you know, this is
the woman's issue" Right?

00:15:24.040 --> 00:15:25.470
You and I sit on transportation.

00:15:25.470 --> 00:15:26.770
What's more important
to women than--

00:15:26.770 --> 00:15:28.070
&gt;&gt;Colleen Shogan: Right.

00:15:28.070 --> 00:15:29.370
&gt;&gt; Rep. Candice Miller:
Transportation.

00:15:29.370 --> 00:15:30.670
Really, right?

00:15:30.670 --> 00:15:32.000
Whatever they're-- whether they're
flying or being in their car or--

00:15:32.000 --> 00:15:33.300
&gt;&gt; Colleen Shogan: Exactly.

00:15:33.300 --> 00:15:35.330
&gt;&gt;Rep. Candice Miller: Safety in
rail or-- you know everything.

00:15:35.330 --> 00:15:37.840
And I'm the Vice Chair of the
Homeland Security Committee.

00:15:37.840 --> 00:15:40.160
What's more important
to women than security?

00:15:40.160 --> 00:15:42.270
Security of the homeland, etcetera.

00:15:42.270 --> 00:15:44.040
But it has changed over the years.

00:15:44.040 --> 00:15:46.340
Because where it was a negative.

00:15:46.340 --> 00:15:49.290
Then at one point it seemed they
said, "Well people would now vote

00:15:49.290 --> 00:15:50.590
for you because you are a woman."

00:15:50.590 --> 00:15:51.890
&gt;&gt; Colleen Shogan: Right.

00:15:51.890 --> 00:15:53.190
&gt;&gt;Rep. Janice Hahn: Right.

00:15:53.190 --> 00:15:54.490
&gt;&gt; Rep. Candice Miller:
And really I think

00:15:54.490 --> 00:15:55.790
if it can just be because
of the merits.

00:15:55.790 --> 00:15:58.020
That's really where we all need to
go but I've also always said this.

00:15:58.020 --> 00:16:00.840
I think we need more women
to be involved in politics.

00:16:00.840 --> 00:16:02.190 position:56%
Whether you're democrat, republican.

00:16:02.190 --> 00:16:03.630
Whether you're running for
Congress or you're running

00:16:03.630 --> 00:16:05.480
for your local school board.

00:16:05.480 --> 00:16:06.830
We need to have more women.

00:16:06.830 --> 00:16:08.790
We need to have their view.

00:16:08.790 --> 00:16:13.400
And I think it is for all of
us that do hold public office

00:16:13.400 --> 00:16:15.750
to conduct ourselves well.

00:16:15.750 --> 00:16:18.640
As well as we can because
you know what?

00:16:18.640 --> 00:16:20.080
It's very generational.

00:16:20.080 --> 00:16:22.710
And the next generation of
women need to be thinking

00:16:22.710 --> 00:16:27.380
about how they can succeed in
politics and have an impact.

00:16:27.380 --> 00:16:30.580
Because it is-- we do
have a different mindset.

00:16:30.580 --> 00:16:34.830
We are all biological
beings after all, right?

00:16:34.830 --> 00:16:37.800
&gt;&gt; Rep. Janice Hahn: I-- am
pleased with the evolution

00:16:37.800 --> 00:16:42.500
of seeing more women
participating in politics.

00:16:42.500 --> 00:16:47.340
Particularly running for
office and being elected.

00:16:47.340 --> 00:16:51.370
I think the evolution
has helped, you know,

00:16:51.370 --> 00:16:53.610
those of us who are
women and in office.

00:16:53.610 --> 00:16:57.010
And those who may be
thinking about it.

00:16:57.010 --> 00:16:58.650
When I first ran for office,

00:16:58.650 --> 00:17:03.210
there were very few women
who were my role models.

00:17:03.210 --> 00:17:04.750
Who had been elected to office.

00:17:04.750 --> 00:17:10.790
Very few. In fact, my staff
always cracks up at this story.

00:17:10.790 --> 00:17:12.090
Wasn't really funny at the time.

00:17:12.090 --> 00:17:17.290
But when I went through my
divorce, my ex actually filed

00:17:17.290 --> 00:17:18.890
for full custody of the children.

00:17:18.890 --> 00:17:21.930
Because he said if I
was elected to office,

00:17:21.930 --> 00:17:24.250
it would make me an unfit mother.

00:17:24.250 --> 00:17:25.550
&gt;&gt; Colleen Shogan: Wow.

00:17:25.550 --> 00:17:26.850 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Rep. Janice Hahn: So yeah I know.

00:17:26.850 --> 00:17:28.150
You kind of laugh about that now.

00:17:28.150 --> 00:17:32.210
But you know there was this
feeling even you know in the'90's.

00:17:32.210 --> 00:17:33.850
It's hard to believe.

00:17:33.850 --> 00:17:36.990
That there was still this
feeling that that's not

00:17:36.990 --> 00:17:40.420
where a woman really belonged
was in the political arena.

00:17:40.420 --> 00:17:44.010
So I think it helps
that more women are--

00:17:44.010 --> 00:17:45.780
running for office
and being elected.

00:17:45.780 --> 00:17:48.470
And as Candice said, you
know, we need more women.

00:17:48.470 --> 00:17:51.410
In congress, we're
only 20% of women.

00:17:51.410 --> 00:17:53.860
Even though we're 50%
of the population.

00:17:53.860 --> 00:17:57.240
We're only 20% of the
members of Congress.

00:17:57.240 --> 00:18:01.400
You know, I think one of the
statistics that was amazing

00:18:01.400 --> 00:18:02.710
to me when I got elected.

00:18:02.710 --> 00:18:04.700
I, you know, all the
years in Congress.

00:18:04.700 --> 00:18:09.950
There'd only been 212, you
know, women elected, you know.

00:18:09.950 --> 00:18:11.290
And now of course--

00:18:11.290 --> 00:18:12.590
&gt;&gt; Rep. Candice Miller:
It's hard, yeah.

00:18:12.590 --> 00:18:14.310
&gt;&gt; Rep. Janice Hahn: We're you
know kind of upping that number.

00:18:14.310 --> 00:18:18.110
But I do believe that
women come to the table

00:18:18.110 --> 00:18:20.630 position:56%
with a different set of experiences.

00:18:20.630 --> 00:18:23.610
I do believe we have sort
of a different perspective.

00:18:23.610 --> 00:18:25.310
And I like the way we govern.

00:18:25.310 --> 00:18:30.250
I think we govern more--
with more collaboration.

00:18:30.250 --> 00:18:34.860
I think we like to find
common ground and consensus.

00:18:34.860 --> 00:18:39.490
And solve problems so I
like the way women govern.

00:18:39.490 --> 00:18:44.360
But I'm wondering if we're almost--
it's now, it's going the other way.

00:18:44.360 --> 00:18:50.950
Because when I'm looking to
recruit for political offices.

00:18:50.950 --> 00:18:52.680
I'm looking for good women.

00:18:52.680 --> 00:18:55.090
I have a hard time now.

00:18:55.090 --> 00:18:58.440
There are women who now,
you know, have careers.

00:18:58.440 --> 00:19:01.840
And actually watching politics,

00:19:01.840 --> 00:19:04.030
particularly during
this presidential year.

00:19:04.030 --> 00:19:06.040
There's a lot of women
that are like,

00:19:06.040 --> 00:19:07.490
"I don't really want to do that.

00:19:07.490 --> 00:19:08.920
You know, that's really nasty.

00:19:08.920 --> 00:19:11.060
That's-- do we really want to
put our families through that?

00:19:11.060 --> 00:19:16.320
Do I really want to, you know, have
everything in my life scrutinized?"

00:19:16.320 --> 00:19:21.500
So I think it's-- I'm finding less
women now who are wanting to run.

00:19:21.500 --> 00:19:24.370
They'll be involved, will
help you on your campaign.

00:19:24.370 --> 00:19:26.950
More and more women are
understanding what it means

00:19:26.950 --> 00:19:30.690
to make a contribution to a-- to
a woman who's running for office.

00:19:30.690 --> 00:19:33.720
But I'm thinking women
are sort of now, you know,

00:19:33.720 --> 00:19:36.820
like not as excited
about being in office.

00:19:36.820 --> 00:19:40.940
Because of what's happened
to our politics of civility.

00:19:40.940 --> 00:19:45.050
Which sometimes you wonder
if that even exists anymore.

00:19:45.050 --> 00:19:46.350
&gt;&gt; Colleen Shogan: I'm
going to ask you to both--

00:19:46.350 --> 00:19:47.960
you got into this a little
bit Representative Hahn.

00:19:47.960 --> 00:19:51.350 position:56%
But I need to ask you both to engage
in the thought experiment with us.

00:19:51.350 --> 00:19:53.440
As you said, 20% of members

00:19:53.440 --> 00:19:56.590
of Congress are women
in the current Congress.

00:19:56.590 --> 00:20:00.070
And I want to ask you, what
would the institution--

00:20:00.070 --> 00:20:01.680
what would congress look like?

00:20:01.680 --> 00:20:06.610
Or how would it operate differently
if 50% of its members were women?

00:20:06.610 --> 00:20:10.920
Or even 51% of its
members were women?

00:20:10.920 --> 00:20:15.970
How would the institution
operate differently if at all?

00:20:15.970 --> 00:20:18.190
&gt;&gt; Rep. Candice Miller: I do
think it would be a bit different.

00:20:18.190 --> 00:20:22.180
I do think-- I think most of us
would agree that women have a bit

00:20:22.180 --> 00:20:25.020
of a different perspective
on how they approach things.

00:20:25.020 --> 00:20:29.260
Whatever your political ideology
is, more of the cultural way

00:20:29.260 --> 00:20:30.790
that you approach various things.

00:20:30.790 --> 00:20:32.530
Where you are trying
to reach a consensus.

00:20:32.530 --> 00:20:36.200
I think more often than just you
know, "Okay I don't agree with you.

00:20:36.200 --> 00:20:37.500
I'm going to put on
the war paint here.

00:20:37.500 --> 00:20:38.800
We're going, you know?

00:20:38.800 --> 00:20:40.800
Let's just think about
how we might be able

00:20:40.800 --> 00:20:42.100
to get through these things."

00:20:42.100 --> 00:20:44.240
And now, I'm not talking
from an ideology standpoint.

00:20:44.240 --> 00:20:45.540
&gt;&gt; Colleen Shogan: Right.

00:20:45.540 --> 00:20:46.880
&gt;&gt; Rep. Candice Miller: But just
the approach to problem solving.

00:20:46.880 --> 00:20:50.030
I think is a bit different.

00:20:50.030 --> 00:20:54.010
And-- so I think in-- of all
the various issues in that.

00:20:54.010 --> 00:20:56.440
If we just had more
voices for women.

00:20:56.440 --> 00:20:58.450
I think-- I think that
would be an important thing.

00:20:58.450 --> 00:20:59.750
But I will agree with you.

00:20:59.750 --> 00:21:02.980
I think where you had an
easier time recruiting women.

00:21:02.980 --> 00:21:05.050
Because I've done candidate
recruitment for my party.

00:21:05.050 --> 00:21:06.350
&gt;&gt; Rep. Janice Hahn: Right.

00:21:06.350 --> 00:21:07.650
&gt;&gt; Rep. Candice Miller: I
know you have for you party.

00:21:07.650 --> 00:21:11.200
It does seem it's a-- it's a--
it's a little more difficult now.

00:21:11.200 --> 00:21:13.180
And-- which is not good.

00:21:13.180 --> 00:21:14.480
&gt;&gt; Colleen Shogan: No.

00:21:14.480 --> 00:21:15.780
&gt;&gt; Rep. Candice Miller: It's
not good for the country.

00:21:15.780 --> 00:21:17.810
Although with all of our
problems, only having 20%

00:21:17.810 --> 00:21:19.140
in the Congress, I'll tell you.

00:21:19.140 --> 00:21:22.630
You know one of the opportunities
I've had in this job is travel.

00:21:22.630 --> 00:21:23.930
You know, you have as well.

00:21:23.930 --> 00:21:28.620
But I can remember going to
Afghanistan and we landed in Kabul.

00:21:28.620 --> 00:21:30.250
Which you know is sort
of like a saucer, right?

00:21:30.250 --> 00:21:31.910
With all the mountain
range around it

00:21:31.910 --> 00:21:33.280
and all the snow melt
was coming down.

00:21:33.280 --> 00:21:34.950
And these children
are standing there

00:21:34.950 --> 00:21:37.050
in the snow melt with no shoes.

00:21:37.050 --> 00:21:38.350
And you know, you could
just see they were--

00:21:38.350 --> 00:21:40.590
they're not going to
make it, you know?

00:21:40.590 --> 00:21:43.050
And they don't have
any facilities there

00:21:43.050 --> 00:21:44.620
for their women or their children.

00:21:44.620 --> 00:21:46.730
These-- some of these societies,
I'm sorry, they just don't care

00:21:46.730 --> 00:21:48.290
about their women so much.

00:21:48.290 --> 00:21:50.750
And then traveling to
we went to see Karzai.

00:21:50.750 --> 00:21:53.520
And traveling to the
Presidential Palace,

00:21:53.520 --> 00:21:55.710
it was like teeming with people.

00:21:55.710 --> 00:21:58.200
And I kept saying, "Well
where are the women?

00:21:58.200 --> 00:21:59.500
Where are they?"

00:21:59.500 --> 00:22:00.800
It's so bizarre.

00:22:00.800 --> 00:22:03.040
So for all of our problems,
you know,

00:22:03.040 --> 00:22:05.720
I tell young women
that all the time.

00:22:05.720 --> 00:22:07.700
Just go do it man.

00:22:07.700 --> 00:22:09.620
Because you-- have
opportunities here.

00:22:09.620 --> 00:22:10.920
You might have challenges

00:22:10.920 --> 00:22:12.270
but you don't have the
challenges your sisters

00:22:12.270 --> 00:22:13.920
in many other countries have.

00:22:13.920 --> 00:22:15.220
So take advantage.

00:22:15.220 --> 00:22:18.510
&gt;&gt; Rep. Janice Hahn: Anyhow I
was thinking about this question.

00:22:18.510 --> 00:22:21.080
What would run differently
if there were more women?

00:22:21.080 --> 00:22:22.380
I don't know.

00:22:22.380 --> 00:22:23.680
Maybe we would carpet all
the marble halls [laughter].

00:22:23.680 --> 00:22:27.210
Because there's so
hard on our high heels.

00:22:27.210 --> 00:22:28.720
&gt;&gt; Rep. Candice Miller: This
is a sensible shoe caucus.

00:22:28.720 --> 00:22:30.020
&gt;&gt; Rep. Janice Hahn: I know.

00:22:30.020 --> 00:22:34.090
I got shin splints my first
year in Congress [laughter].

00:22:34.090 --> 00:22:38.150
But I-- think beyond that you know.

00:22:38.150 --> 00:22:43.300
I find that my friendships
with the few women

00:22:43.300 --> 00:22:46.510
in Congress are really special.

00:22:46.510 --> 00:22:55.010
And they, you know, it allows me
even across the aisle to find,

00:22:55.010 --> 00:22:57.010
you know, areas of common ground.

00:22:57.010 --> 00:23:00.840
Areas of consensus
and there is not the--

00:23:00.840 --> 00:23:03.220 position:56%
you know, the hostility that exists.

00:23:03.220 --> 00:23:05.960
I think sometimes between the men.

00:23:05.960 --> 00:23:07.260
I mean we don't have testosterone.

00:23:07.260 --> 00:23:09.620
That changes a lot
of things [laughter].

00:23:09.620 --> 00:23:12.890
Changes a lot of the--
you know, the atmosphere.

00:23:12.890 --> 00:23:16.060
It changes a lot of where
you go on a conversation.

00:23:16.060 --> 00:23:20.660
It changes a lot of you know
the agenda of-- the house.

00:23:20.660 --> 00:23:23.130
So I would love to see
more women in Congress.

00:23:23.130 --> 00:23:27.380
I think it would you know
really be an opportunity

00:23:27.380 --> 00:23:30.270
to show you know the world.

00:23:30.270 --> 00:23:33.360
That you know we can be
from different parties

00:23:33.360 --> 00:23:35.250
and yet we can get along.

00:23:35.250 --> 00:23:36.690
And we can find common ground.

00:23:36.690 --> 00:23:40.470
And I think it would-- I think it
would help if we had more women.

00:23:40.470 --> 00:23:43.590
I'd love to see more women
you know chairs of committees.

00:23:43.590 --> 00:23:44.980
I just think, you know--

00:23:44.980 --> 00:23:46.280
&gt;&gt; Rep. Candice Miller: You
don't think one is enough?

00:23:46.280 --> 00:23:47.580
&gt;&gt; Rep. Janice Hahn: I know right?

00:23:47.580 --> 00:23:48.880
I know. You know--

00:23:48.880 --> 00:23:50.180
&gt;&gt; Rep. Candice Miller:
One is not enough?

00:23:50.180 --> 00:23:51.810
We could have a few more [laughs].

00:23:51.810 --> 00:23:54.820
&gt;&gt; Rep. Janice Hahn: I, you know,
I think we run things differently.

00:23:54.820 --> 00:23:59.220 position:56%
Again, I think we just bring
different perspectives to the table.

00:23:59.220 --> 00:24:01.680
&gt;&gt; Colleen Shogan: Unfortunately
you're both retiring from Congress

00:24:01.680 --> 00:24:03.100
and leaving us later this year.

00:24:03.100 --> 00:24:06.400
I wonder if you could share with
us some of your future plans.

00:24:06.400 --> 00:24:09.950
And what you're most
looking forward to doing?

00:24:09.950 --> 00:24:12.560
&gt;&gt; Rep. Candice Miller:
Well you know first of all.

00:24:12.560 --> 00:24:15.490
When I first came here I
never thought I would stay

00:24:15.490 --> 00:24:16.860
as long as I have stayed.

00:24:16.860 --> 00:24:18.160
&gt;&gt; Colleen Shogan: Huh?

00:24:18.160 --> 00:24:19.460
&gt;&gt;Rep. Candice Miller: And I
know a lot of people say that.

00:24:19.460 --> 00:24:21.520
And I think also people
say, "You sort of know

00:24:21.520 --> 00:24:22.820
when is your time to go" right?

00:24:22.820 --> 00:24:24.120
&gt;&gt; Colleen Shogan: Right.

00:24:24.120 --> 00:24:25.420
&gt;&gt; Rep. Candice Miller:
When you're done.

00:24:25.420 --> 00:24:26.720
And that was really true for me.

00:24:26.720 --> 00:24:28.260
But I thought I would be
here 6 years, 8 years maybe.

00:24:28.260 --> 00:24:30.080
You know I'm going
to tell you though.

00:24:30.080 --> 00:24:32.440
It's like any other job I guess.

00:24:32.440 --> 00:24:33.850
Maybe more so than a lot of jobs.

00:24:33.850 --> 00:24:35.420
It's sort of insidious, you know.

00:24:35.420 --> 00:24:37.340
Pretty soon you think,
"Well now I'm the chairman.

00:24:37.340 --> 00:24:39.710
I can't leave now or I got
this issue I'm working on.

00:24:39.710 --> 00:24:41.010
I can't leave now".

00:24:41.010 --> 00:24:42.310
Well pretty soon you're
never going to leave.

00:24:42.310 --> 00:24:43.610
And then they're going to
maybe take you out on a gurney.

00:24:43.610 --> 00:24:46.060
And I don't want go
that way [laughter].

00:24:46.060 --> 00:24:48.160
And I truly love Michigan.

00:24:48.160 --> 00:24:49.540
I'm a Michigan girl.

00:24:49.540 --> 00:24:51.450
And I want to go home to Michigan.

00:24:51.450 --> 00:24:55.090
So I'm looking forward
to whatever it is next.

00:24:55.090 --> 00:24:56.390
I'm not quite sure what?

00:24:56.390 --> 00:24:58.180
But I'll tell you the
experiences that I have had here.

00:24:58.180 --> 00:25:00.340
There's absolutely no second.

00:25:00.340 --> 00:25:03.800
And so I-- you know,
I don't know how--

00:25:03.800 --> 00:25:06.300
I hope to be of value at somewhere.

00:25:06.300 --> 00:25:08.170
I might run for office
again, you know.

00:25:08.170 --> 00:25:09.670
I might not.

00:25:09.670 --> 00:25:12.210
I might go back into
the private sector.

00:25:12.210 --> 00:25:14.150
But I also say this.

00:25:14.150 --> 00:25:15.660
This is just my personal feeling.

00:25:15.660 --> 00:25:19.240
I-- really do think the
founding fathers always thought

00:25:19.240 --> 00:25:20.950
that for Congress.

00:25:20.950 --> 00:25:23.800
Particularly in the House, that
you would come from various sectors

00:25:23.800 --> 00:25:25.680
of your-- of the country.

00:25:25.680 --> 00:25:27.880
And do your thing for
some period of time.

00:25:27.880 --> 00:25:29.930
And then you would go back.

00:25:29.930 --> 00:25:31.840
Not just be here forever.

00:25:31.840 --> 00:25:33.690
And really if you want
to know the truth

00:25:33.690 --> 00:25:35.650
and this is not a partisan thing.

00:25:35.650 --> 00:25:38.510
Sometimes I think part of the
gridlock problems we have is

00:25:38.510 --> 00:25:40.150
because some people don't leave.

00:25:40.150 --> 00:25:41.450
They never go.

00:25:41.450 --> 00:25:43.300
So even when you have a
Presidential election.

00:25:43.300 --> 00:25:45.760
Now you have a new President but
then you still have-- then they go.

00:25:45.760 --> 00:25:47.060
"Oh okay well here's this new guy.

00:25:47.060 --> 00:25:49.000
But here they-- they've
all been here."

00:25:49.000 --> 00:25:50.300
&gt;&gt; Colleen Shogan: Right.

00:25:50.300 --> 00:25:51.600
&gt;&gt; Rep. Candice Miller:
So I don't know.

00:25:51.600 --> 00:25:53.960
That's-- I'm not-- and I'm not
saying about any particular person.

00:25:53.960 --> 00:25:58.890
I'm just saying in my observation
I do think it's the people's house.

00:25:58.890 --> 00:26:02.260
You know, I don't-- I don't know
what the right amount of time is.

00:26:02.260 --> 00:26:05.240
But I don't think it
should be forever.

00:26:05.240 --> 00:26:06.540
&gt;&gt; Colleen Shogan: Okay.

00:26:06.540 --> 00:26:09.500
Representative Hahn.

00:26:09.500 --> 00:26:10.800
&gt;&gt; Rep. Janice Hahn: So I'm--

00:26:10.800 --> 00:26:13.580
well have been here
only 5 years this July.

00:26:13.580 --> 00:26:15.510
And when I end my term
at the end of the year,

00:26:15.510 --> 00:26:17.070
it'll be like 5 and a half years.

00:26:17.070 --> 00:26:19.430
But I am going home to Los Angeles.

00:26:19.430 --> 00:26:22.770
And I'm currently-- I'm
going to be on the ballot

00:26:22.770 --> 00:26:25.110
for County Supervisor
in Los Angeles.

00:26:25.110 --> 00:26:28.730
So it's the same job my
dad did for 40 years.

00:26:28.730 --> 00:26:32.010
I sort of grew up in the
County of Los Angeles.

00:26:32.010 --> 00:26:36.180
And kind of really understood what
a supervisor was in LA County.

00:26:36.180 --> 00:26:39.370
So I'm really looking
forward to going home.

00:26:39.370 --> 00:26:45.200
I think-- you know, when I said I
cut my teeth on the City Council.

00:26:45.200 --> 00:26:48.800
I-- really believe for
me, it's a better fit

00:26:48.800 --> 00:26:50.730
for me, is local government.

00:26:50.730 --> 00:26:54.740
I like the idea of sort of
where the rubber meets the road.

00:26:54.740 --> 00:26:58.740
I like you know seeing my
constituents in the grocery store.

00:26:58.740 --> 00:27:02.160
And you know they want their tree
trimmed or their pothole filled

00:27:02.160 --> 00:27:04.800
or their sidewalk-- I like that.

00:27:04.800 --> 00:27:08.350
I like actually seeing
the fruits of my labor.

00:27:08.350 --> 00:27:10.090
Seeing a problem and solving it.

00:27:10.090 --> 00:27:13.130
There's only 5 members of the
County Board of Supervisors.

00:27:13.130 --> 00:27:17.410
And actually with my candidacy,
there is a historic opportunity

00:27:17.410 --> 00:27:20.610
for 3 females to be on the LA
County Board of Supervisors.

00:27:20.610 --> 00:27:22.180
For the first time in the
history of the County.

00:27:22.180 --> 00:27:23.480
My dad was there.

00:27:23.480 --> 00:27:25.070
It was you know the
old boy's network.

00:27:25.070 --> 00:27:27.810
It was-- they called
them the 5 kings.

00:27:27.810 --> 00:27:32.350 position:56%
And-- but now with diversity and
more women I look forward to working

00:27:32.350 --> 00:27:36.170
with 2 other women, you
know, out of-- out of 5.

00:27:36.170 --> 00:27:39.760
To really, you know, talk about
you know issues that matter

00:27:39.760 --> 00:27:41.540
to most people in the
county of Los Angeles.

00:27:41.540 --> 00:27:44.380
So I'm-- I know where I'm going.

00:27:44.380 --> 00:27:49.220
And I feel good but I-- will
look back on my time here.

00:27:49.220 --> 00:27:54.650
As of course being such
an amazing experience.

00:27:54.650 --> 00:27:59.920
Really such an opportunity to
serve as a member of Congress.

00:27:59.920 --> 00:28:05.600
It's really been a very
special and satisfying to me.

00:28:05.600 --> 00:28:10.200
But frustrating also
just in the gridlock.

00:28:10.200 --> 00:28:15.980
You know I think I landed in one of
the more partisan political divides

00:28:15.980 --> 00:28:18.050
that Congress has been
in a long time.

00:28:18.050 --> 00:28:19.990
And I don't enjoy it.

00:28:19.990 --> 00:28:22.650
I decided I don't enjoy
partisan politics.

00:28:22.650 --> 00:28:25.310
Los Angeles County
Supervisor is non-partisan.

00:28:25.310 --> 00:28:28.000
You just you know you look at
a problem and you solve it.

00:28:28.000 --> 00:28:31.920
And you don't really have
to worry about one side

00:28:31.920 --> 00:28:33.700
or the other making
political points.

00:28:33.700 --> 00:28:35.100
And I think it'll be
a better fit for me.

00:28:35.100 --> 00:28:39.450
And if I never get on a
plane again [laughter].

00:28:39.450 --> 00:28:41.340
It will be too soon.

00:28:41.340 --> 00:28:45.450
I have a 3,000 mile
commute every week.

00:28:45.450 --> 00:28:48.860
I fly here on Mondays and fly
home on Thursdays every week.

00:28:48.860 --> 00:28:50.410
And that has taken a toll.

00:28:50.410 --> 00:28:51.710
&gt;&gt; Colleen Shogan: Oh yeah, yeah.

00:28:51.710 --> 00:28:54.830 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Rep. Janice Hahn: So-- which is
why I was trying to pass legislation

00:28:54.830 --> 00:28:57.130
about seat sizes [laughter].

00:28:58.970 --> 00:29:00.270
&gt;&gt; Rep. Candice Miller:
Yeah [laughs].

00:29:00.270 --> 00:29:01.570
Why? We have 7 inches.

00:29:01.570 --> 00:29:03.590
How much room do you need there?

00:29:03.590 --> 00:29:08.070
&gt;&gt; Rep. Janice Hahn: After 6 hours
like, "Oh, it's so uncomfortable."

00:29:08.070 --> 00:29:09.370
&gt;&gt; Colleen Shogan: Chairman Miller.

00:29:09.370 --> 00:29:10.670
We have one last question for you.

00:29:10.670 --> 00:29:11.970
It's sort of a humorous question.

00:29:11.970 --> 00:29:15.460
I wonder if you could tell
us about your nickname?

00:29:15.460 --> 00:29:18.680
And-- "old goat" and how
you got that nickname?

00:29:18.680 --> 00:29:21.870
And why you are so
proud to have earned it?

00:29:21.870 --> 00:29:24.720
&gt;&gt; Rep. Candice Miller: Well,
jeez the old goat [laughter].

00:29:24.720 --> 00:29:28.230 position:56%
I told you I used to race sailboats.

00:29:28.230 --> 00:29:29.530
&gt;&gt; Colleen Shogan: Right.

00:29:29.530 --> 00:29:30.830
&gt;&gt; Rep. Candice Miller:
And my whole family does.

00:29:30.830 --> 00:29:34.320
But anyway, there is
sort of a Marquis race--

00:29:34.320 --> 00:29:36.770
Freshwater Sailboat Race
in the world really.

00:29:36.770 --> 00:29:38.430
Is on Lake Huron.

00:29:38.430 --> 00:29:40.440
It's Port Huron to Mackinac.

00:29:40.440 --> 00:29:43.310 position:56%
Any of you heard of Mackinac Island.

00:29:43.310 --> 00:29:44.610
&gt;&gt;Colleen Shogan: Yeah.

00:29:44.610 --> 00:29:45.910
&gt;&gt; Rep. Candice Miller: So there's
this Port Huron to Mackinac race.

00:29:45.910 --> 00:29:47.840
There's another one in
Chicago to Mackinac.

00:29:47.840 --> 00:29:49.330
And-- first of all I
will tell you I was

00:29:49.330 --> 00:29:52.470
in the first all-female crew
in the Chicago Mackinac.

00:29:52.470 --> 00:29:55.290
And also the first all-female crew
in the Port Huron to Mackinac.

00:29:55.290 --> 00:29:56.590
&gt;&gt; Colleen Shogan: Yay.

00:29:56.590 --> 00:29:57.890
&gt;&gt; Rep. Candice Miller:
Many years ago.

00:29:57.890 --> 00:29:59.190
I was 15 at the time.

00:29:59.190 --> 00:30:00.490
&gt;&gt; Colleen Shogan: Very cool.

00:30:00.490 --> 00:30:01.790
&gt;&gt; Rep. Candice Miller:
"Oh my gosh, I can't even--

00:30:01.790 --> 00:30:03.090
" I'm really dating myself.

00:30:03.090 --> 00:30:05.710 position:56%
But anyway, in Port Huron race after
you compete in 25 of these races.

00:30:05.710 --> 00:30:08.760
They induct you into what they
call the Old Goat Society.

00:30:08.760 --> 00:30:10.520
And I've done 29 of them.

00:30:10.520 --> 00:30:12.810
So I am actually an old nanny goat.

00:30:12.810 --> 00:30:14.400
&gt;&gt; Colleen Shogan: Oh!

00:30:14.400 --> 00:30:15.700
&gt;&gt; Rep. Candice Miller: And--

00:30:15.700 --> 00:30:17.000
&gt;&gt;Colleen Shogan: You're a goat.

00:30:17.000 --> 00:30:18.300
&gt;&gt; Rep. Candice Miller:
And I know this to be true.

00:30:18.300 --> 00:30:21.050
I am the only old nanny goat
in the United States count.

00:30:21.050 --> 00:30:22.570
&gt;&gt; Colleen Shogan:
Wow, there you go.

00:30:22.570 --> 00:30:23.870
&gt;&gt; Rep. Candice Miller: [Laughs].

00:30:23.870 --> 00:30:26.800
&gt;&gt; Rep. Janice Hahn: And you
can keep that title [laughter].

00:30:26.800 --> 00:30:29.540
&gt;&gt; Rep. Candice Miller:
I earned it baby.

00:30:29.540 --> 00:30:30.840
&gt;&gt; Rep. Janice Hahn: Right.

00:30:30.840 --> 00:30:32.140
&gt;&gt; Rep. Candice Miller: [Laughs].

00:30:32.140 --> 00:30:33.440
&gt;&gt; Colleen Shogan: So now we--

