Robert.

00:30:48.980 --> 00:30:52.550
&gt;&gt; Robert: I'd like to ask the
members if there were any books

00:30:52.550 --> 00:30:54.020
that they've read along the way

00:30:54.020 --> 00:30:57.240
that influenced their
thinking in Congress?

00:30:57.240 --> 00:30:59.970
Or influenced their
thinking about leadership?

00:30:59.970 --> 00:31:04.830
&gt;&gt; Rep. Candice Miller:
I'm not going to say

00:31:04.830 --> 00:31:07.130
"The Art of the Deal" [laughter].

00:31:09.970 --> 00:31:13.750
I don't know if there was
ever any one particular book

00:31:13.750 --> 00:31:16.490
that has influenced me.

00:31:16.490 --> 00:31:20.240
But-- I don't know if I
can answer that question.

00:31:20.240 --> 00:31:22.160
Really I can't think
of one particular book

00:31:22.160 --> 00:31:23.760
that really influenced me.

00:31:23.760 --> 00:31:25.110
People more I think.

00:31:25.110 --> 00:31:27.810
Individual experiences and that.

00:31:27.810 --> 00:31:30.180
&gt;&gt; Rep. Janice Hahn: So I had
fund reading "Game Change".

00:31:30.180 --> 00:31:34.180
And I had fun reading "This Town."

00:31:34.180 --> 00:31:38.490
Those were really a little
bit behind the scenes

00:31:38.490 --> 00:31:40.860
political campaigns.

00:31:40.860 --> 00:31:44.520
And kind of what goes into
that and how that translates

00:31:44.520 --> 00:31:47.580
to actually being in governance.

00:31:47.580 --> 00:31:50.890
I found those books--
and I enjoy the books

00:31:50.890 --> 00:31:53.310
that were having our
congressional dialogue.

00:31:53.310 --> 00:31:54.610
&gt;&gt;Rep. Candice Miller: Yes.

00:31:54.610 --> 00:31:55.910
&gt;&gt;Rep. Janice Hahn:
"Lyndon Johnson",

00:31:55.910 --> 00:31:58.210
"Reagan" and "Kennedy" coming up.

00:31:58.210 --> 00:32:01.320
I've really enjoyed those to kind

00:32:01.320 --> 00:32:03.060
of really take us back
to the way it was.

00:32:03.060 --> 00:32:06.010 position:56%
It was like, again though, in those
books it's like where are the women?

00:32:06.010 --> 00:32:07.310
But--

00:32:07.310 --> 00:32:08.610
&gt;&gt; Colleen Shogan: Yup, I did.

00:32:08.610 --> 00:32:12.690
&gt;&gt; Rep. Janice Hahn: Still
those really have in--

00:32:12.690 --> 00:32:16.100
have-- reminded me where I am.

00:32:16.100 --> 00:32:18.520
And reminded me who's
gone before me.

00:32:18.520 --> 00:32:24.100
And reminded me of the, you
know, sometimes incredible fights

00:32:24.100 --> 00:32:30.210
that went on to achieve certain
policies for the American people.

00:32:30.210 --> 00:32:32.090
So I've really enjoyed those.

00:32:32.090 --> 00:32:33.390 position:56%
&gt;&gt; Rep. Candice Miller: That's true.

00:32:33.390 --> 00:32:34.690
The history of this place--

00:32:34.690 --> 00:32:35.990
&gt;&gt; Rep. Janice Hahn: I know.

00:32:35.990 --> 00:32:37.290
&gt;&gt; Rep. Candice Miller:
Is sometimes, you know,

00:32:37.290 --> 00:32:38.590
honestly I'm sure we
all have this feeling.

00:32:38.590 --> 00:32:40.080
You know sometimes in the winter
when-- it's days are short.

00:32:40.080 --> 00:32:43.000
And you're walking across
Independence Avenue over here

00:32:43.000 --> 00:32:44.570
to go vote at the Capitol.

00:32:44.570 --> 00:32:47.260
And there's the Capitol all lit
up and you know you're walking--

00:32:47.260 --> 00:32:50.090
you're looking at the
lady Freedom Statue.

00:32:50.090 --> 00:32:51.900
Thinking, "Man you go girl".

00:32:51.900 --> 00:32:53.200
That's really something, right?

00:32:53.200 --> 00:32:54.500
&gt;&gt; Rep. Janice Hahn: I know, right?

00:32:54.500 --> 00:32:55.800
&gt;&gt;Rep. Candice Miller: And you
just pinch yourself thinking.

00:32:55.800 --> 00:32:57.630
"How, what-- am I even--
how did I even get here?"

00:32:57.630 --> 00:32:59.870
With all the history
that has happened here.

00:32:59.870 --> 00:33:03.320
And really in this Capitol
it's quite something.

