&gt;&gt; You spoke to the importance of
the diversity in gender in Congress.

00:33:16.330 --> 00:33:20.780
And I'd like to hear both of you
speak to how you think we are doing

00:33:20.780 --> 00:33:24.880
in terms of diversity and
ethnicity in Congress?

00:33:24.880 --> 00:33:31.370
And what are our losses
and gains related to that?

00:33:31.370 --> 00:33:33.440
&gt;&gt; Rep. Candice Miller: We are
not doing particularly well.

00:33:33.440 --> 00:33:34.740
I don't think.

00:33:34.740 --> 00:33:37.210
Certainly on my side of the isle,
we need to do a much better job.

00:33:37.210 --> 00:33:40.240
And don't think that
we're not all aware of it.

00:33:40.240 --> 00:33:42.820
I will tell you though, I
think in politics generally.

00:33:42.820 --> 00:33:45.390
I mentioned to you earlier
I mean I was the Secretary

00:33:45.390 --> 00:33:46.800
of State of Michigan.

00:33:46.800 --> 00:33:49.870
And when I first ran for that
job I was running against

00:33:49.870 --> 00:33:54.130
and older African American
incumbent.

00:33:54.130 --> 00:33:57.550
And the truth-- and here I was
running as the first female, right?

00:33:57.550 --> 00:33:59.990
And really I will tell
you in all sincerity.

00:33:59.990 --> 00:34:03.110
That race-- I don't
think anyone ever said.

00:34:03.110 --> 00:34:05.890
"Oh well we need to vote for him
because he's an African American.

00:34:05.890 --> 00:34:08.230
Or we need to vote for her
because she's the woman."

00:34:08.230 --> 00:34:09.590
It really was about the issues.

00:34:09.590 --> 00:34:13.150
And I have always thought about
that because at some point that's

00:34:13.150 --> 00:34:17.130
where we need to be
as a country, right?

00:34:17.130 --> 00:34:22.020 position:56%
Whatever the-- whatever the-- issues
are, is always got to be paramount.

00:34:22.020 --> 00:34:25.530
And you know this is the land
of opportunity and all men

00:34:25.530 --> 00:34:27.730
and women are created equal.

00:34:27.730 --> 00:34:31.170
So but we need to do
a much better job.

00:34:31.170 --> 00:34:33.770
&gt;&gt; Rep. Janice Hahn: I will say
I'm proud of the Democratic caucus.

00:34:33.770 --> 00:34:37.260
Actually has-- this is
I think our first time

00:34:37.260 --> 00:34:42.750
when we've actually had a
majority of minority representation

00:34:42.750 --> 00:34:44.300
in our Democratic caucus.

00:34:44.300 --> 00:34:46.950
So we have more women,
more African Americans

00:34:46.950 --> 00:34:49.260
and more Latinos and
Asian Americans.

00:34:49.260 --> 00:34:52.870
Than I think ever before
in our caucus so--

00:34:52.870 --> 00:34:56.080
but I-- do-- I agree you know.

00:34:56.080 --> 00:34:59.150
It should be about the issues.

00:34:59.150 --> 00:35:02.160
And I actually represent a
minority district right now.

00:35:02.160 --> 00:35:04.520
I represent a district that's--

00:35:04.520 --> 00:35:09.170
you know, 48% Latino,
28% African American.

00:35:09.170 --> 00:35:14.760
So I represent a very you
know diverse district.

00:35:14.760 --> 00:35:16.310
But I-- it's sort of
like women though.

00:35:16.310 --> 00:35:19.790
I do believe people come to the
table with different experiences.

00:35:19.790 --> 00:35:25.020
And I think for those, you
know, our diverse ethnicity.

00:35:25.020 --> 00:35:28.900
Our African Americans, our Latinos,
our Asian Americans, our LGBT.

00:35:28.900 --> 00:35:31.600
They come with a different
set of experiences

00:35:31.600 --> 00:35:33.310
and a different perspective.

00:35:33.310 --> 00:35:37.990
And they have seen life
differently and I think that makes

00:35:37.990 --> 00:35:42.390
for a better congress
and a better America.

00:35:42.390 --> 00:35:44.400
And you do the best you can

00:35:44.400 --> 00:35:47.070
to represent the people
that have elected you.

00:35:47.070 --> 00:35:52.720
But I do love the different
perspectives that come

00:35:52.720 --> 00:35:54.920
from all over this country.

00:35:54.920 --> 00:35:58.510
And people who have lived a
different life than I have.

00:35:58.510 --> 00:36:01.000
And I think that makes
for better policy.

00:36:01.000 --> 00:36:02.600
That makes for better judgement.

00:36:02.600 --> 00:36:07.810
That makes for I think
a better understanding

00:36:07.810 --> 00:36:14.190
of what the American
people are wanting from us.

00:36:14.190 --> 00:36:15.490
&gt;&gt; Colleen Shogan:
Any other questions?

00:36:15.490 --> 00:36:19.460
Oh. Oh David, oh okay, go ahead.

00:36:19.460 --> 00:36:20.760
I didn't--

00:36:20.760 --> 00:36:22.060
&gt;&gt; David Mao: Reflecting--
thank you very much

00:36:22.060 --> 00:36:23.360
for your presentation today.

00:36:23.360 --> 00:36:25.680
It was fascinating.

00:36:25.680 --> 00:36:27.390
Reflecting on your careers though.

00:36:27.390 --> 00:36:29.360
If you were speaking
to a young woman

00:36:29.360 --> 00:36:32.170
who is starting out
in politics today.

00:36:32.170 --> 00:36:33.970
Whether it be on the
local level, state level

00:36:33.970 --> 00:36:35.710
or even a new member of Congress.

00:36:35.710 --> 00:36:38.030
What one piece of advice
would you give them to think

00:36:38.030 --> 00:36:42.940 position:56%
about to guide them along their way?

00:36:42.940 --> 00:36:46.100
&gt;&gt;Rep. Candice Miller: I would say
that they need to find the balance

00:36:46.100 --> 00:36:49.210
between their professional
life and their family.

00:36:49.210 --> 00:36:50.820 position:56%
And that they can find that balance.

00:36:50.820 --> 00:36:52.120
&gt;&gt;Rep. Janice Hahn:
How do you do that?

00:36:52.120 --> 00:36:53.420
&gt;&gt; Rep. Candice Miller:
Yeah [laughs].

00:36:53.420 --> 00:36:54.720
Well they need to do it.

00:36:54.720 --> 00:36:56.020
Otherwise and that's--

00:36:56.020 --> 00:36:57.640
I think that's why women
don't want to do it, right?

00:36:57.640 --> 00:37:01.090
And often times because not
only are they the caregivers

00:37:01.090 --> 00:37:02.390
for their children.

00:37:02.390 --> 00:37:04.790
They're usually the caregivers
if they have older parents.

00:37:04.790 --> 00:37:06.310
They're all of these things, right?

00:37:06.310 --> 00:37:09.240
And then women also have a--
just for whatever reason.

00:37:09.240 --> 00:37:12.400
Whether it's because of
the way we were all raised.

00:37:12.400 --> 00:37:17.090
We have an aversion to asking
somebody for money for us, right?

00:37:17.090 --> 00:37:18.390
&gt;&gt; Colleen Shogan: Yeah.

00:37:18.390 --> 00:37:19.690
&gt;&gt; Rep. Candice Miller: You don't
mind asking people for money

00:37:19.690 --> 00:37:20.990
for the local schoolboard.

00:37:20.990 --> 00:37:23.380
Or the you know the
hospital board or something.

00:37:23.380 --> 00:37:26.330
But for yourself, sometimes
you think it's sort of--

00:37:26.330 --> 00:37:28.720
you just have to get over
all of these things you know.

00:37:28.720 --> 00:37:33.070
So I just tell women that you
know I think they need to think

00:37:33.070 --> 00:37:34.950
about finding that balance.

00:37:34.950 --> 00:37:38.770
And that it's important that
we do have more women involved.

00:37:38.770 --> 00:37:40.490
And I actually go-- I try to speak

00:37:40.490 --> 00:37:43.070
to local high school
kids when I can.

00:37:43.070 --> 00:37:44.680
I have throughout my entire career.

00:37:44.680 --> 00:37:47.720
Because really if a woman
is going to be thinking

00:37:47.720 --> 00:37:50.090
about a political career.

00:37:50.090 --> 00:37:52.290
You need to at least plant
the seed at that time

00:37:52.290 --> 00:37:56.490
that politics can be an honorable
profession for them to think about.

00:37:56.490 --> 00:37:58.970
And that they should
consider such a thing.

00:37:58.970 --> 00:38:01.490
And that they might want to go out
and think about getting involved

00:38:01.490 --> 00:38:05.670
in a campaign or-- do something
where they hopefully you know.

00:38:05.670 --> 00:38:08.610
If there's 40 in a room
then hopefully there's 1

00:38:08.610 --> 00:38:10.230
that will catch the
political bug and think

00:38:10.230 --> 00:38:13.250
about running for something.

00:38:13.250 --> 00:38:14.550
&gt;&gt;Rep. Janice Hahn: I know.

00:38:14.550 --> 00:38:16.400
And you know actually
you kind of touched

00:38:16.400 --> 00:38:17.700 position:56%
on it earlier in something you said.

00:38:17.700 --> 00:38:21.020
But it is true still to this
day women do have an advantage

00:38:21.020 --> 00:38:24.940
because of the-- trust issue.

00:38:24.940 --> 00:38:27.420
The-- if there's just a woman
and a man on the ballot.

00:38:27.420 --> 00:38:28.790
Your pollsters will tell you.

00:38:28.790 --> 00:38:33.690
Women get a couple of points just
because we're more believable.

00:38:33.690 --> 00:38:38.300
And when the negative
campaigning comes against us.

00:38:38.300 --> 00:38:41.530
Less and less voters believe that.

00:38:41.530 --> 00:38:43.300
They don't believe that about us.

00:38:43.300 --> 00:38:45.460
That all the things our
opponents are saying.

00:38:45.460 --> 00:38:47.590
So there is still an advantage.

00:38:47.590 --> 00:38:51.800
If I was giving a woman
any kind of advice,

00:38:51.800 --> 00:38:53.650
particularly if she
was coming to Congress.

00:38:53.650 --> 00:38:58.600
I would say have 2 complete
sets of wardrobes [laughter].

00:39:00.730 --> 00:39:03.900
Have everything you need at home
and everything you need here.

00:39:03.900 --> 00:39:06.920
Don't be trying to remember
what shoes go with what outfit.

00:39:06.920 --> 00:39:10.750 position:56%
Because you know they're going to
be in the other location [laughter].

00:39:10.750 --> 00:39:18.250
But I think seriously I would just
remind women to know their value.

00:39:18.250 --> 00:39:19.550
Know their value.

00:39:19.550 --> 00:39:22.400
I know Mika Brzezinski does this--

00:39:22.400 --> 00:39:25.470
thing every year about
women knowing their value.

00:39:25.470 --> 00:39:31.090
And then mostly women still have
a hard time knowing their value

00:39:31.090 --> 00:39:32.480
and knowing why they're important.

00:39:32.480 --> 00:39:34.930 position:56%
And knowing the role that they play.

00:39:34.930 --> 00:39:37.150 position:56%
Because when you're--
particularly in Congress when you're

00:39:37.150 --> 00:39:39.210
in the minority you know.

00:39:39.210 --> 00:39:41.820
It's you know, it takes
a little more courage.

00:39:41.820 --> 00:39:44.840
It takes a little more
bravery to speak up.

00:39:44.840 --> 00:39:49.430
To think that your idea is
really worth you know pushing.

00:39:49.430 --> 00:39:52.020
That your legislation makes sense.

00:39:52.020 --> 00:39:54.350
That you know you really
are doing a good thing.

00:39:54.350 --> 00:40:00.920
Because I still think women tend
to sometimes not value themselves

00:40:00.920 --> 00:40:03.080
in the way that our
male counterparts do.

00:40:03.080 --> 00:40:06.650
So it does take a little bravery I
think to be back here as a woman.

00:40:06.650 --> 00:40:12.040
And to speak up and to not be
you know in any way intimidated.

00:40:12.040 --> 00:40:15.680
About the questions that
you ask in committees,

00:40:15.680 --> 00:40:18.190
legislation that you're
pushing forward.

00:40:18.190 --> 00:40:23.270
Because it can be an intimidating
place I think sometimes.

00:40:23.270 --> 00:40:25.290
&gt;&gt; Colleen Shogan:
Any further questions?

00:40:25.290 --> 00:40:27.190
Yes?

00:40:27.190 --> 00:40:30.510
&gt;&gt; Hi, you both mentioned
that some of the friendships

00:40:30.510 --> 00:40:33.730
that you have made in Congress
were particularly important to you.

00:40:33.730 --> 00:40:36.500
And I was wondering when
you were first starting out.

00:40:36.500 --> 00:40:37.990
If there was a particular person

00:40:37.990 --> 00:40:39.740
or a particular moment
you can remember?

00:40:39.740 --> 00:40:43.600
Where another woman in
Congress really helped you out

00:40:43.600 --> 00:40:45.990
or showed you the ropes
or something like that?

00:40:45.990 --> 00:40:52.300
&gt;&gt;Rep. Candice Miller: [Laughs]
I don't know if there was one--

00:40:52.300 --> 00:40:53.920
again one particular moment.

00:40:53.920 --> 00:40:56.530
But I've had, you know, some good
friendships that have been there.

00:40:56.530 --> 00:41:01.050 position:56%
Some of the women that I came into
to Congress with are no longer here.

00:41:01.050 --> 00:41:04.740
You know even though people think
that we all stay here forever.

00:41:04.740 --> 00:41:08.430
Actually the truth is there's a lot
more turnover than you'd imagine.

00:41:08.430 --> 00:41:10.870
And some of the women that I've--

00:41:10.870 --> 00:41:14.700
that I was good friends
with have left on their own.

00:41:14.700 --> 00:41:16.760
Some got beat.

00:41:16.760 --> 00:41:18.060
Different things.

00:41:18.060 --> 00:41:20.990
But I do think women
have a tendency to again,

00:41:20.990 --> 00:41:22.990
whether we're Democrats
or Republicans.

00:41:22.990 --> 00:41:25.880
To talk about our family,
the challenges

00:41:25.880 --> 00:41:27.530
that we're facing at home.

00:41:27.530 --> 00:41:29.630
I mean you know we
have this woman's room,

00:41:29.630 --> 00:41:34.590
the Lindy Boggs room
off the-- which really.

00:41:34.590 --> 00:41:36.000
It was Boehner who finally put

00:41:36.000 --> 00:41:39.080
in the ladies room off
the-- off the house floor.

00:41:39.080 --> 00:41:40.820
Not that we need one, okay?

00:41:40.820 --> 00:41:42.560
[laughter] Because--
you're sort of saying,

00:41:42.560 --> 00:41:44.170
"Well where's the bathrooms
over here?

00:41:44.170 --> 00:41:45.600
Well, the men's room is over here.

00:41:45.600 --> 00:41:47.770
I mean what-- is it
you're looking for?

00:41:47.770 --> 00:41:50.690
Okay." But anyway [laughs]

00:41:50.690 --> 00:41:55.040
but the Lindy Boggs room is
sort of where the women go.

00:41:55.040 --> 00:41:58.070
&gt;&gt; Rep. Janice Hahn: The only room
in the Capitol named for a woman.

00:41:58.070 --> 00:41:59.450
&gt;&gt; Rep. Candice Miller: Yeah, yeah.

00:41:59.450 --> 00:42:04.420
And-- gosh sometimes when we're
here at night voting late.

00:42:04.420 --> 00:42:10.100 position:56%
I can remember one member who was on
the phone obviously very distraught.

00:42:10.100 --> 00:42:12.810
And was saying you know-- I don't
know whatever was happening.

00:42:12.810 --> 00:42:15.830
And she said, "You
know I'm so far away."

00:42:15.830 --> 00:42:18.980
And just the anguish
and you know women--

00:42:18.980 --> 00:42:21.370
you know you've got
children, grandchildren.

00:42:21.370 --> 00:42:23.820
You know your spouses,
your family, whatever.

00:42:23.820 --> 00:42:27.930
It is-- and so I think women have
a tendency that-- recognizing that.

00:42:27.930 --> 00:42:31.460
And want another in
challenges that-- and I'm not--

00:42:31.460 --> 00:42:32.950
believe I'm not whining about it.

00:42:32.950 --> 00:42:35.700
I'm just saying that that
you know we do have that.

00:42:35.700 --> 00:42:38.820
So it's just a different situation.

00:42:38.820 --> 00:42:41.160
&gt;&gt;Rep. Janice Hahn: So when I came
here I really hardly knew anybody.

00:42:41.160 --> 00:42:45.090
I had really not spent that much
time coming to Washington DC even

00:42:45.090 --> 00:42:48.480
for lobbying trips
with my City Council.

00:42:48.480 --> 00:42:50.180
I really did not spend
that much time here.

00:42:50.180 --> 00:42:51.840
So I really didn't know anybody.

00:42:51.840 --> 00:42:55.280
Well one of the first people
I wanted to say hello to

00:42:55.280 --> 00:42:56.640
and introduce myself was

00:42:56.640 --> 00:43:00.570
to my Republican colleague,
Ted Poe from Texas.

00:43:00.570 --> 00:43:04.230
Because Ted and I are
the only 2 alumnae

00:43:04.230 --> 00:43:06.900
from Abilene Christian
University in Abilene, Texas,

00:43:06.900 --> 00:43:09.290
that are members of Congress.

00:43:09.290 --> 00:43:12.500
So I you know went
and said hello to Ted.

00:43:12.500 --> 00:43:16.470
And we've-- we struck up,
obviously a conversation based

00:43:16.470 --> 00:43:20.570
on our shared history
with the university.

00:43:20.570 --> 00:43:22.970
And then I asked him to co-chair--

00:43:22.970 --> 00:43:27.690
one of the first things that I
did was created a port caucus.

00:43:27.690 --> 00:43:30.510
You know based on our
nation's sea ports.

00:43:30.510 --> 00:43:32.320
It really had never
been done before.

00:43:32.320 --> 00:43:35.620
And I represented the ports
of Los Angeles and Long Beach.

00:43:35.620 --> 00:43:40.480 position:56%
And he of course represented a bunch
of ports in Texas, Houston area.

00:43:40.480 --> 00:43:45.010
And I said, "Would you co-chair
this port caucus with me?"

00:43:45.010 --> 00:43:47.100
We now have about 100
members of Congress,

00:43:47.100 --> 00:43:48.850
both Republicans and Democrats.

00:43:48.850 --> 00:43:51.590
Some of them who don't
even have a port.

00:43:51.590 --> 00:43:52.890
But they're happy to be in a--

00:43:52.890 --> 00:43:56.630
you know, sort of a
collegial bipartisan effort.

00:43:56.630 --> 00:44:02.440
And it was a big thrill 2 years ago
when the American Authority of--

00:44:02.440 --> 00:44:05.340
Association of Port
Authorities named Ted

00:44:05.340 --> 00:44:09.450
and I as joint port
people of the year.

00:44:09.450 --> 00:44:12.830
So that was really special.

00:44:12.830 --> 00:44:14.880
You know, speaking of
the Lindy Boogs room.

00:44:14.880 --> 00:44:22.280
So every Wednesday morning at
8:00 AM there is a group of women.

00:44:22.280 --> 00:44:29.890
Diane Black, Marsha Blackburn,
Virginia Fox, Christy [inaudible]

00:44:29.890 --> 00:44:33.550
and Susan-- Senator
Susan Collins and myself.

00:44:33.550 --> 00:44:36.250
And sometimes my colleague
from California Lois Capps

00:44:36.250 --> 00:44:40.890
and we actually have a bible
study in the Lindy Boggs room.

00:44:40.890 --> 00:44:45.970
And it's you know sometimes
we-- pray and read the bible.

00:44:45.970 --> 00:44:48.420
But mostly it's talking--

00:44:48.420 --> 00:44:49.720
&gt;&gt;Rep. Candice Miller: Yeah.

00:44:49.720 --> 00:44:51.020
&gt;&gt; Rep. Janice Hahn:
About our experience here.

00:44:51.020 --> 00:44:54.990
And having someone who understands
what we're going through.

00:44:54.990 --> 00:44:58.890
And we can talk to them when
you can't really-- you know.

00:44:58.890 --> 00:45:01.700
Because your constituents don't
really want to hear you whine

00:45:01.700 --> 00:45:03.060
about your experience, right?

00:45:03.060 --> 00:45:04.360
&gt;&gt; Rep. Candice Miller: Right.

00:45:04.360 --> 00:45:06.090
&gt;&gt; Rep. Janice Hahn: And-- it's
not appropriate to complain

00:45:06.090 --> 00:45:08.770
about your experience
with your constituents.

00:45:08.770 --> 00:45:13.500
But it sure is nice to
have some girlfriends even

00:45:13.500 --> 00:45:14.890
from across the aisle.

00:45:14.890 --> 00:45:20.580
That you know we share the same
rhythm, the experience, the timing.

00:45:20.580 --> 00:45:21.940
We have the same votes.

00:45:21.940 --> 00:45:25.210
You know we have the
same schedules basically.

00:45:25.210 --> 00:45:27.380
And it helps to talk to them.

00:45:27.380 --> 00:45:30.940
So that's been a real
special time for me.

00:45:30.940 --> 00:45:34.970
Now when I tell my Democratic
colleagues who is in this.

00:45:34.970 --> 00:45:38.660
You know, they can't believe
that I'm you know hanging

00:45:38.660 --> 00:45:41.640
out with the likes of those women.

00:45:41.640 --> 00:45:42.940
But I [laughter] really--

00:45:42.940 --> 00:45:44.240
&gt;&gt; Rep. Candice Miller: Well wait

00:45:44.240 --> 00:45:45.560
until they find out
what you did today.

00:45:45.560 --> 00:45:47.940
&gt;&gt; Rep. Janice Hahn: I
know right [laughter] I got

00:45:47.940 --> 00:45:49.240
to hang out with you.

00:45:49.240 --> 00:45:50.810
But I find it--

00:45:50.810 --> 00:45:52.110
&gt;&gt; Rep. Candice Miller:
Don't tell anyone.

00:45:52.110 --> 00:45:53.410
&gt;&gt; Rep. Janice Hahn: I know.

00:45:53.410 --> 00:45:54.800
I find it's something
that I do for myself.

00:45:54.800 --> 00:45:58.190
And it helps me get
through my week here.

00:45:58.190 --> 00:45:59.490
&gt;&gt; Rep. Candice Miller:
You know what?

00:45:59.490 --> 00:46:01.450
I just have to make a comment, an
observation talking about friends

00:46:01.450 --> 00:46:02.750
on the other side of the aisle.

00:46:02.750 --> 00:46:04.720
Because I see my good friend
Debbie Dingell from Michigan,

00:46:04.720 --> 00:46:06.410
who is a freshman member.

00:46:06.410 --> 00:46:08.410
But she and I go way back.

00:46:08.410 --> 00:46:10.700
She-- grew up actually
in my district.

00:46:10.700 --> 00:46:14.720
Now she lives further down--
stream, down the Detroit River.

00:46:14.720 --> 00:46:18.740
But her and I this week in honor
of Michigan's History month.

00:46:18.740 --> 00:46:21.330
Are going to bring in
Rosie the Riveters.

00:46:21.330 --> 00:46:23.560
And you know and South
East Michigan was known

00:46:23.560 --> 00:46:24.980
as the arsenal of democracy.

00:46:24.980 --> 00:46:26.970 position:56%
And so many of-- during World War II

00:46:26.970 --> 00:46:30.300
and these women literally
built the armaments

00:46:30.300 --> 00:46:32.710
that led the entire world to peace.

00:46:32.710 --> 00:46:34.070
Remarkable women and you hear

00:46:34.070 --> 00:46:36.400
about all these honor flight
coming for World War II.

00:46:36.400 --> 00:46:37.700
&gt;&gt; Rep. Janice Hahn: Yeah.

00:46:37.700 --> 00:46:39.000
&gt;&gt; Rep. Candice Miller:
And she and I said,

00:46:39.000 --> 00:46:40.300
"We need to bring these Rosie's".

00:46:40.300 --> 00:46:42.810
And so the Library of
Congress has been very,

00:46:42.810 --> 00:46:48.900
very helpful in putting together--
well we have some great posters.

00:46:48.900 --> 00:46:50.500 position:56%
That we got out of the archives here

00:46:50.500 --> 00:46:51.800
that we're going to
give the Rosie's.

00:46:51.800 --> 00:46:56.330
And you know they're in their late
80's, 90's remarkable stories.

00:46:56.330 --> 00:47:01.390
But again something that you can do
across the aisle to make an impact

00:47:01.390 --> 00:47:05.400
in recognition of unbelievable
ta-- patriots certainly.

00:47:05.400 --> 00:47:07.990
&gt;&gt; Colleen Shogan: I
see another question.

00:47:07.990 --> 00:47:12.690
&gt;&gt; Okay I don't really
have a question.

00:47:12.690 --> 00:47:17.470
But I just want to tell you both
how much I admire all the women

00:47:17.470 --> 00:47:19.230
in Congress and in the Senate.

00:47:19.230 --> 00:47:21.710
I can say just listening
to you today.

00:47:21.710 --> 00:47:23.010
You both have children.

00:47:23.010 --> 00:47:24.310
You both have grandchildren.

00:47:24.310 --> 00:47:29.080
And I'm the wife of Rick Allen,
George XII so I can tell you now.

00:47:29.080 --> 00:47:30.790
I like my role as spouse.

00:47:30.790 --> 00:47:32.090
I don't want to be you.

00:47:32.090 --> 00:47:34.980 position:56%
But I [laughter] and I say it a lot.

00:47:34.980 --> 00:47:39.880
I don't know how you deal with--
I have -- I guilt it on myself.

00:47:39.880 --> 00:47:44.520
But I heap that guilt here
with children back home.

00:47:44.520 --> 00:47:49.790
And a mother, 94 year old mother
and I don't even have to be here.

00:47:49.790 --> 00:47:51.880
You know I can go home
when I need to.

00:47:51.880 --> 00:47:54.100
But I just admire you all so much.

00:47:54.100 --> 00:47:58.390 position:56%
I think it's-- incredible and you
both seem to have it-- have it down.

00:47:58.390 --> 00:48:00.770 position:56%
So whatever you're doing, I want you

00:48:00.770 --> 00:48:03.130
to tell me later how
you do it [laughter].

00:48:03.130 --> 00:48:05.130
Maybe it's because I have
to keep up with my husband

00:48:05.130 --> 00:48:06.430
up here, you think that's it?

00:48:06.430 --> 00:48:07.730
That's the hard part?

00:48:07.730 --> 00:48:09.030
&gt;&gt;Rep. Candice Miller:
He's a very busy guy.

00:48:09.030 --> 00:48:10.330
He's a very busy guy.

00:48:10.330 --> 00:48:11.630
&gt;&gt;Rep. Janice Hahn: And
you know that's nice

00:48:11.630 --> 00:48:12.930
that you're here too with him.

00:48:12.930 --> 00:48:15.590
It's nice to have your
spouse or your family here.

00:48:15.590 --> 00:48:19.210
I think one of the things that is
particularly difficult for a lot

00:48:19.210 --> 00:48:22.060
of members of congress is
when after a really long day.

00:48:22.060 --> 00:48:24.520
You go home and you shut
the door to your apartment.

00:48:24.520 --> 00:48:25.820
And you are alone.

00:48:25.820 --> 00:48:27.120
You are not with your family.

00:48:27.120 --> 00:48:28.420
They are somewhere else.

00:48:28.420 --> 00:48:30.930
And see those are the times
that you know your heart kind

00:48:30.930 --> 00:48:32.300
of hurts a little bit.

00:48:32.300 --> 00:48:36.440 position:56%
That you're not surrounded by hearth
and home and a loving family member.

00:48:36.440 --> 00:48:38.300
So we-- it's nice that you--

00:48:38.300 --> 00:48:42.580
I put both my spouse pen's in my
hope chest at home [laughter].

00:48:42.580 --> 00:48:46.800
&gt;&gt; Colleen Shogan: We have
time for one more question.

00:48:46.800 --> 00:48:49.660
&gt;&gt; About staff, it
feels that there are--

00:48:49.660 --> 00:48:52.630 position:56%
I don't know the numbers but
anecdotally there a lot of women now

00:48:52.630 --> 00:48:54.980
who seem to be in senior staff
positions in the Congress.

00:48:54.980 --> 00:48:56.280 position:56%
And I wonder if you could talk a bit

00:48:56.280 --> 00:48:59.210
about what impact you
see that having?

00:48:59.210 --> 00:49:03.490
And generally about--
women in staff positions?

00:49:03.490 --> 00:49:06.070
&gt;&gt; Rep. Candice Miller: You know
I don't really know what the

00:49:06.070 --> 00:49:08.090
percentage is of women staff.

00:49:08.090 --> 00:49:12.570
But there certainly is a lot-- I'm
sure it's a much higher percentage

00:49:12.570 --> 00:49:14.230
of staff than it is actual members.

00:49:14.230 --> 00:49:16.720 position:56%
I mean my Chief of Staff is a woman.

00:49:16.720 --> 00:49:19.050
My district director is a woman.

00:49:19.050 --> 00:49:20.350
&gt;&gt; Rep. Janice Hahn: Mine too.

00:49:20.350 --> 00:49:21.650
&gt;&gt; Rep. Candice Miller:
But you know,

00:49:21.650 --> 00:49:25.040
I have a mix gender
wise in both offices.

00:49:25.040 --> 00:49:28.790
So-- I mean I've always had--

00:49:28.790 --> 00:49:30.790
again, I mean I really do look

00:49:30.790 --> 00:49:32.850
at the qualifications
of the individuals.

00:49:32.850 --> 00:49:34.150
Because guess what?

00:49:34.150 --> 00:49:35.450
If they're not doing a good job.

00:49:35.450 --> 00:49:38.080
You know, you're probably going
to be out of your own job.

00:49:38.080 --> 00:49:43.410
And so-- but there are certainly
many, many more women now I think

00:49:43.410 --> 00:49:47.130
in particular senior levels.

00:49:47.130 --> 00:49:51.310
Chiefs of-- on the
committees, staff directors,

00:49:51.310 --> 00:49:52.870
all of those kinds of things.

00:49:52.870 --> 00:49:54.970
And that's a very important
part of it.

00:49:54.970 --> 00:49:59.160
I mean staff is the
most critical component

00:49:59.160 --> 00:50:02.600
for any member of congress.

00:50:02.600 --> 00:50:05.100
&gt;&gt;Rep. Janice Hahn: Yeah so
my Chief of Staff is a woman.

00:50:05.100 --> 00:50:06.650
My scheduler is a woman.

00:50:06.650 --> 00:50:08.600
My communications director
is a woman.

00:50:08.600 --> 00:50:10.130
My district director is a woman.

00:50:10.130 --> 00:50:12.320
Actually at one point
I was very happy

00:50:12.320 --> 00:50:14.700
because back here in
DC we were all women.

00:50:14.700 --> 00:50:18.360
We finally had an interloper a
guy that we-- [laughter] hired.

00:50:18.360 --> 00:50:19.950
And he's there.

00:50:19.950 --> 00:50:23.710
But I do think there's more
equality and opportunities

00:50:23.710 --> 00:50:27.520
at the staff level on
the hill is my sense.

00:50:27.520 --> 00:50:30.320
That there really they're
all equals.

00:50:30.320 --> 00:50:34.700
And some of them have some
incredible institutional memory.

00:50:34.700 --> 00:50:40.890 position:56%
My chief of staff worked for Barbara
Boxer, worked for Jane Harman,

00:50:40.890 --> 00:50:43.330 position:56%
did a lot of work in transportation.

00:50:43.330 --> 00:50:49.900
So she's a real source of
information and knowledge for me.

00:50:49.900 --> 00:50:54.750
Particularly coming from you know
Los Angeles and not really being

00:50:54.750 --> 00:50:56.670
in Washington DC politics.

00:50:56.670 --> 00:51:01.330 position:56%
So there is a-- I think there's
more equality and more opportunities

00:51:01.330 --> 00:51:03.920
at the staff level for women.

00:51:03.920 --> 00:51:06.170
&gt;&gt; Colleen Shogan: Well this has
been a tremendous conversation.

00:51:06.170 --> 00:51:07.680
And would everybody please join me

00:51:07.680 --> 00:51:10.000
in thanking Chairman Miller
and Representative Hahn.

00:51:10.000 --> 00:51:11.300
&gt;&gt; Rep. Candice Miller: Thank you.

00:51:11.300 --> 00:51:12.600
Thank you.

